{"name":"Saint Syrus - The Veteran","type":"npc","img":"icons/equipment/head/helm-bascinet-reinforced.webp","system":{"npcType":"adversary","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":false,"biography":"Saint Syrus is the oldest of Saint George's six Paladins, a grizzled veteran who has fought Broken Tales for decades. His experience has taught him to trust only his own judgment, making him both incredibly effective and frustratingly stubborn. Syrus has seen countless supernatural threats, studied their patterns, and developed countermeasures for virtually every type of Gift or magical ability. His vast experience allows him to negate the effect of a Hunter's Gift once per Scene—he always seems to know exactly how to counter whatever supernatural ability is being used. This makes him a particularly dangerous opponent for Hunters who rely heavily on their Gifts. When a Hunter activates a powerful Gift expecting it to turn the tide of battle, Syrus calmly explains the countermeasure he's prepared and nullifies it entirely. However, Syrus's reliance on his own judgment is also his weakness. He's set in his ways, dismissive of new ideas or approaches he hasn't personally validated. He won't listen to Martha's doubts or Trebizond's questions—he's fought monsters for decades and knows what they are. This stubbornness means he's unlikely to be convinced that Saint George is wrong, but it also means he can be outmaneuvered by tactics he hasn't encountered before. Hunters who use creative or unconventional approaches may catch him off-guard, as his experience becomes a liability when facing something genuinely new.","attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":2,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I am a Paladin in service of Saint George","His word, for me, is law","Years of training made me adept at fighting Broken Tales","I am the oldest of the Paladins and I only trust my own judgment"],"gifts":[{"name":"Paladin - Veteran","description":"Once per Scene, Syrus can negate the effect of a Gift activated by a Hunter. The Saint will find a method to counter Gifts, drawn from his great experience—he might interrupt a ritual, throw holy water to disrupt magic, use a specific ward he's prepared, or simply know the weakness of that particular ability. When he does this, the Hunter's Gift activates but has no effect, and any Soma or resources spent are still consumed. This makes Syrus extremely dangerous to Hunters who rely on one powerful Gift as their primary strategy."}],"conditions":[],"notes":"Syrus is Paladin #5 (roll 1d6 to determine). Most dangerous to Gift-reliant Hunters—can negate one Gift per Scene. Has countermeasures for almost everything due to decades of experience. Stubborn and dismissive of others' judgment—won't listen to Martha or Trebizond's doubts. Unlikely to be convinced Saint George is wrong. Weakness: set in his ways, can be outmaneuvered by truly creative/unconventional tactics he hasn't seen before. Experience becomes liability against novel approaches. Voice: Gruff, dismissive, authoritative. Mannerisms: Crosses arms, shakes head at others' suggestions, prepared stance."},"_id":"0b92bad966f1d363"}
{"name":"Saint Theodore - The Furious","type":"npc","img":"icons/weapons/axes/axe-double-engraved-red.webp","system":{"npcType":"adversary","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":false,"biography":"Saint Theodore is one of Saint George's six Paladins, and he is consumed by the ecstasy of battle. For Theodore, combat is the sweetest of pleasures—a religious experience that brings him closer to divine purpose. His fury in battle makes him one of the most dangerous Paladins. Theodore always inflicts additional wounds when he strikes, and even successful Defense Checks cannot fully protect against his rage-fueled attacks. The only way to avoid his bonus damage is to spend an Increment to nullify it. In combat, Theodore is aggressive and relentless, seeking out the strongest opponents and engaging them with wild abandon. He laughs during battle, quotes scripture with fervor, and treats each exchange of blows as a sacrament. Unlike Demetrius who protects, or Martha who shows compassion, Theodore exists to destroy those Saint George has deemed enemies. His weakness is his predictability—his love of battle means he can be baited, manipulated into charging, or separated from his fellow Paladins by appealing to his desire for glorious combat. However, underestimating Theodore is fatal. He's an expert warrior whose fury is backed by years of training. He views the Hunters as worthy opponents—monsters who will provide him with the greatest battle of his life. Smart Hunters will find ways to neutralize him without engaging in direct combat, as facing him head-on plays to his greatest strength.","attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":2,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I am a Paladin in service of Saint George","His word, for me, is law","Years of training made me adept at fighting Broken Tales","The ecstasy of battle is for me the sweetest of pleasures"],"gifts":[{"name":"Paladin - Furious","description":"Theodore always inflicts 1 Additional Wound when raging against an enemy. He still inflicts 1 Wound even if the Defense Check is a successful Outcome. The only way to avoid the effect of this Gift is to spend an Increment to cancel the Wound. This means Theodore is guaranteed to deal at least 1 Wound on every attack unless the defender has Increment available. When he achieves a successful attack normally, he deals 2 Wounds total (1 base + 1 from Furious)."}],"conditions":[],"notes":"Theodore is Paladin #3 (roll 1d6 to determine). Most dangerous in direct combat—ALWAYS deals at least 1 Wound unless Increment spent. Predictable due to battle-lust: can be baited, separated, or manipulated into charging. Laughs during combat, quotes scripture fervently, treats battle as sacrament. Seeks strongest opponents. Avoid engaging him directly if possible—neutralize through environment, traps, or forcing him to waste attacks on obstacles. Voice: Loud, passionate, laughs frequently. Mannerisms: Aggressive stance, eager movements, grins during combat."},"_id":"2f251ba4a36c2f1c"}
{"name":"Saint Margaret - The Ambitious","type":"npc","img":"icons/weapons/polearms/spear-hooked-gold.webp","system":{"npcType":"adversary","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":false,"biography":"Saint Margaret is one of Saint George's six Paladins, but unlike the others who serve out of devotion or duty, Margaret serves out of ambition. She wants to affirm her role in the Church and ultimately overthrow 'that arrogant Saint George' to take his position. This secret agenda makes her simultaneously the most dangerous and the most exploitable of the Paladins. Margaret's Gift makes her stronger the more Saint George is weakened—her Opposition Level increases by 1 for each Wound Saint George has suffered, and she can take an immediate additional action whenever Saint George takes damage. This means that in prolonged battles where Saint George is being worn down, Margaret becomes progressively more powerful, potentially even surpassing her master. She fights with extra vigor when Saint George is threatened, not out of loyalty, but because his suffering empowers her. Margaret is brilliant, ruthless, and calculating. She's playing a long game, waiting for the perfect moment to make her move against Saint George. Smart Hunters can exploit this in multiple ways: they might make a deal with Margaret to betray Saint George in exchange for helping her achieve her ambitions, they might reveal her treachery to Saint George to sow discord among the Paladins, or they might deliberately wound Saint George to make Margaret more powerful and uncontrollable, forcing the other Paladins to deal with her. Of all the Paladins, Margaret is the most likely to make a deal with the Hunters—but she's also the least trustworthy, as her ambition outweighs any sense of honor or loyalty.","attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":2,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I am a Paladin in service of Saint George","His word, for me, is law","Years of training made me adept at fighting Broken Tales","I want to affirm my role in the Church and overthrow that arrogant Saint George"],"gifts":[{"name":"Paladin - Ambition","description":"Margaret increases her Opposition Level by 1 for each Wound that Saint George has suffered (if Saint George has 2 Wounds, Margaret's OL becomes 7). Once per Scene, when Saint George suffers 1 Wound, Margaret can immediately perform 1 additional action as she seizes the opportunity. This makes Margaret progressively more dangerous as battles wear on and Saint George is weakened, potentially making her more powerful than her master by the end of a prolonged fight."}],"conditions":[],"notes":"Margaret is Paladin #6 (roll 1d6 to determine). MOST DANGEROUS in prolonged battles—gains +1 OL per Saint George Wound, bonus action when he's hurt. Secret ambition to overthrow Saint George makes her exploitable: can make deals with Hunters, reveal her treachery to cause Paladin discord, or deliberately empower her by wounding Saint George to make her uncontrollable. Most likely to negotiate with Hunters but LEAST trustworthy—ambition trumps honor. Brilliant, ruthless, calculating. Voice: Smooth, confident, hints of superiority. Mannerisms: Watches Saint George constantly, smiles when he's wounded, calculates constantly."},"_id":"3b86fb57a15f4a29"}
{"name":"Saint Demetrius - The Guardian","type":"npc","img":"icons/equipment/shield/heater-crystal-blue.webp","system":{"npcType":"adversary","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":false,"biography":"Saint Demetrius is one of Saint George's six Paladins, renowned for his unwavering dedication to protecting his companions. He places the defense of his allies before his own life, embodying the ideal of selfless service. Demetrius is the shield of the Paladin group—always positioned to intercept attacks meant for others, always ready to throw himself in harm's way. His Gift allows him to take wounds in place of his allies, and when he does so, his Opposition Level increases as his protective fury grows. This makes him increasingly dangerous the more he sacrifices himself. In combat, Demetrius positions himself between enemies and his fellow Paladins, particularly protecting Saint George himself. Smart Hunters can exploit this—by threatening his allies, they can force Demetrius to take multiple wounds, potentially taking him out of the fight while he tries to save everyone. However, this also makes him more dangerous with each wound taken. Demetrius is utterly devoted to his duty and sees no greater honor than dying to protect those he serves. He views the Hunters as threats to his brothers and sisters in faith, and will not hesitate to interpose himself between them and any Paladin—especially if Saint Martha is threatened, as she represents compassion within the group.","attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":2,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I am a Paladin in service of Saint George","His word, for me, is law","Years of training made me adept at fighting Broken Tales","I put the defense of my companions before my own life"],"gifts":[{"name":"Paladin - Guardian","description":"Once per Exchange, Demetrius can take 1 Wound in place of one of his allies (must be within 30 feet and line of sight). When he does this, he increases his Opposition Level by 1 for the rest of the Scene (cumulative—if he takes wounds multiple Scenes, the bonuses stack). This makes him progressively more dangerous as he sacrifices himself. The wound transfer happens automatically if Demetrius chooses—the ally takes no damage, and Demetrius takes the full wound instead."}],"conditions":[],"notes":"Demetrius is Paladin #2 (roll 1d6 to determine which appears). His protective nature can be exploited—threaten his allies to force him to take wounds, potentially eliminating him while making him more dangerous. He always positions between enemies and allies, especially protecting Saint Martha. Works best with other Paladins as he has allies to protect. If isolated, loses much of his effectiveness. Can't be reasoned with—duty and protection are absolute. Voice: Calm and resolute, reassuring to allies. Mannerisms: Shield raised, defensive stance, watches for threats to allies."},"_id":"b17b72aac59c3384"}
{"name":"Saint Martha - The Friendly","type":"npc","img":"icons/magic/holy/angel-winged-humanoid-blue.webp","system":{"npcType":"adversary","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":false,"biography":"Saint Martha is one of Saint George's six Paladins, and she stands apart from the others in a crucial way: she does not believe that Broken Tales should be eradicated, only understood. This compassionate perspective makes her the conscience of the Paladin group and a potential ally for Hunters who can reach her. Martha believes there's a difference between monsters who choose evil and those who are simply misunderstood or corrupted against their will. She joined Saint George's Paladins hoping to protect innocents and bring understanding between humans and the supernatural, not to wage war. When Saint George initiates a Witch Hunt against the Hunters, Martha secretly doubts his judgment—especially if she's witnessed the Hunters performing good deeds or showing mercy. Her Gift makes Hunters reluctant to attack her (receiving 2 Penalties if other Paladins are available as targets), representing both her non-threatening demeanor and the moral difficulty of striking someone who radiates compassion. Smart Hunters will recognize Martha as the key to ending the Witch Hunt peacefully. If they can show her evidence of Saint George's manipulation, or demonstrate through their actions that they're genuinely trying to help people, Martha may be convinced to speak on their behalf or even actively assist them. She's the Paladin most likely to betray Saint George if convinced he's wrong—not out of treachery, but out of a higher loyalty to true justice and compassion.","attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":2,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I am a Paladin in service of Saint George","His word, for me, is law","Years of training made me adept at fighting Broken Tales","I do not think Broken Tales should be eradicated, only understood"],"gifts":[{"name":"Paladin - Friendly","description":"Any Hunter who acts against Martha when there are other Paladins as potential targets will receive 2 Penalties on their action. This represents both Martha's non-threatening demeanor that makes it psychologically difficult to attack her, and her positioning that makes her a harder target when allies are nearby. This only applies when at least one other Paladin is present and available as a target—if Martha is isolated, she loses this protection."}],"conditions":[],"notes":"Martha is Paladin #4 (roll 1d6 to determine). KEY CHARACTER for peaceful resolution—she doubts Saint George's Witch Hunt and can be convinced to help Hunters. Shows compassion, believes in understanding rather than destruction. If shown evidence of manipulation or witnesses Hunters' good deeds, may speak for them or actively assist. Protected by Gift when with other Paladins (2 Penalties to attack her). Most likely to betray Saint George out of higher loyalty to justice. Can be the bridge to redemption. Voice: Gentle, questioning, compassionate. Mannerisms: Hesitates before violence, shows concern for all parties."},"_id":"c23258abf908cecd"}
{"name":"Trebizond - Princess of a Distant Country","type":"npc","img":"icons/weapons/thrown/net-weighted-purple.webp","system":{"npcType":"adversary","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":false,"biography":"Trebizond is a princess from a distant country who serves as one of Saint George's six Paladins. She brings an exotic perspective and arsenal to the Paladins, using unfamiliar weapons and objects from her homeland that surprise and confound opponents. Unlike some of the more rigid Paladins, Trebizond possesses an unshakeable curiosity about new things—a trait that can be both her strength and her weakness. She's fascinated by the cultures and peoples she encounters during her travels with Saint George, and this curiosity sometimes distracts her from her holy mission. Her special equipment includes items like Magic-Finding Dust that reveals hidden enchantments, whips as sharp as blades that can strike from distance, exotic poisons that induce specific effects, or mechanical devices from her homeland that seem almost magical. When she creates a special equipment Descriptor and uses it, her Opposition Level increases to 6, making her a formidable combatant. Smart Hunters can exploit her curiosity—offering to show her something unique or fascinating might distract her or even make her question Saint George's absolute judgments. Of all the Paladins, she's the most likely to be swayed by experiencing something that challenges her worldview.","attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":2,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I am a Paladin in service of Saint George","His word, for me, is law","Years of training made me adept at fighting Broken Tales","Sometimes I am seized by unshakeable curiosity about new things"],"gifts":[{"name":"Paladin - From a Far Country","description":"Trebizond can make use of exotic weapons and objects to surprise opponents. Once per Scene, she can create a Descriptor that represents special equipment, such as 'Magic-Finding Dust' or 'A Whip as Sharp as a Blade' or 'Poison from the Eastern Lands' or 'Mechanical Crossbow of My Homeland'. When using her special equipment, Trebizond increases her Opposition Level by 1 (to 6). The equipment lasts for the Scene and provides tactical advantages beyond just the OL bonus."}],"conditions":[],"notes":"Trebizond is Paladin #1 (roll 1d6 to determine which Paladin appears). Her curiosity is both strength and weakness—she might be distracted by fascinating objects or stories, or convinced to question orders if shown something truly unique. She works well with other Paladins but sometimes pursues her own interests. Can be separated from group by exploiting her curiosity. Voice: Accented, expressive, asks many questions. Mannerisms: Examines everything closely, touches unfamiliar objects."},"_id":"e40856670f14142e"}
